

🎤 Interview Question

You are given an employee DataFrame with the following columns:

emp_id, name, joining_date

Write PySpark code to perform the following tasks:

1. Calculate the number of days an employee has worked until today in a column named days_worked.


2. Add 30 days to the joining_date and store it in next_review_date.


3. Subtract 7 days from the joining_date and store it in previous_week.


4. Add 6 months to the joining_date and store it in confirmation_date.


5. Display the updated DataFrame.



> Assume joining_date is already of DateType.




---

📊 Input Dataset

emp_id	name	joining_date

101	John	2023-01-15
102	David	2022-05-20
103	Alice	2021-11-10
104	Bob	2020-08-01
105	Sam	2024-02-25



---

✅ Expected Output

emp_id	name	joining_date	days_worked	next_review_date	previous_week	confirmation_date

101	John	2023-01-15	Calculated	2023-02-14	2023-01-08	2023-07-15
102	David	2022-05-20	Calculated	2022-06-19	2022-05-13	2022-11-20
103	Alice	2021-11-10	Calculated	2021-12-10	2021-11-03	2022-05-10
104	Bob	2020-08-01	Calculated	2020-08-31	2020-07-25	2021-02-01
105	Sam	2024-02-25	Calculated	2024-03-26	2024-02-18	2024-08-25



---

✅ Recommended Solution

from pyspark.sql.functions import (
    col,
    current_date,
    datediff,
    date_add,
    date_sub,
    add_months
)

df = (
    df.withColumn(
        "days_worked",
        datediff(current_date(), col("joining_date"))
    )
    .withColumn(
        "next_review_date",
        date_add(col("joining_date"), 30)
    )
    .withColumn(
        "previous_week",
        date_sub(col("joining_date"), 7)
    )
    .withColumn(
        "confirmation_date",
        add_months(col("joining_date"), 6)
    )
)

df.show()


